\layout Subsection

Divisor Series
\layout Standard

Consider the series 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M_{d}(x)=(1-\left|x\right|)^{2}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x^{n-1}d(n)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d(n)=\sigma_{0}(n)$
\end_inset 

 is the number of divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 A graph of this function appears below.
 Special values include 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
2M_{d}(1/2) & = & \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}d(n)/2^{n}\\
 & = & \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{2^{n}-1}\\
 & = & 1.60669515241529176...\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 which is known as the Erdos-Borwein constant.
 In general, this series is an example of a Lambert series.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x^{n}d(n)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{x^{n}}{1-x^{n}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note that the sume on the right hand side can be computed a lot more quickly
 than the sum on the left hand side, primarily because the divisor function
 gets more difficult to compute for larger n.
 
